msgid ""
"`vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate<float>` or `vtkFloatArray` have a ValueType of "
"`float`,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:53
msgid ""
"`vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<vtkTypeInt64>` or `vtkSOATypeInt64Array` have a "
"ValueType of `vtkTypeInt64`,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:54
msgid ""
"`vtkConstantArray<vtkTypeInt8>` or `vtkConstantTypeInt8Array` have a "
"ValueType of `vtkTypeInt8`,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:55
msgid "`vtkStringArray` has a ValueType of `vtkStdString`,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:56
msgid ""
"`vtkBitArray` has a ValueType of `unsigned char`, because we can't have bit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:58
msgid ""
"And Array must specify all of the above, i.e. ValueType, DataTypeTag, and "
"ArrayTypeTag, along with an array implementation. This becomes important as "
"`vtkAbstractArray` concrete subclasses will begin to stray from the typical "
"\"array-of-structs\" ordering that has been exclusively used in the past."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:63
msgid ""
"A __dispatch__ is a runtime-resolution of a `vtkAbstractArray`'s ArrayType, "
"and is used to call a section of executable code that has been tailored for "
"that ArrayType. Dispatching has compile-time and run-time components. At "
"compile-time, the possible ArrayTypes to be used are determined, and a "
"worker code template is generated for each type, which is stored in an array "
"so that it can be efficiently accessed using `GetArrayType()` and "
"`GetDataType()` with `O(1)` complexity. At run-time, the correct ArrayType "
"is determined, using `GetArrayType()` and `GetDataType()`, and the proper "
"worker instantiation is called."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:72
msgid ""
"__Template explosion__ refers to a sharp increase in the size of a compiled "
"binary that results from instantiating a template function or class on many "
"different types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:76
msgid "vtkAbstractArray"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:78
msgid ""
"The abstract array type hierarchy in VTK has a unique feature when compared "
"to typical C++ containers: a non-templated base class. All arrays inherit "
"`vtkAbstractArray`. Those containing numeric data inherit `vtkDataArray`, "
"which is a subclass of `vtkAbstractArray`, a common interface that sports a "
"very useful API. Without knowing the underlying ValueType stored in data "
"array, an algorithm or user may still work with any `vtkDataArray` in "
"meaningful ways: The array can be resized, reshaped, read, and rewritten "
"easily using a generic API that substitutes double-precision floating point "
"numbers for the array's actual ValueType. For instance, we can write a "
"simple function that computes the magnitudes for a set of vectors in one "
"array and store the results in another using nothing but the typeless "
"`vtkDataArray` API:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:90
msgid ""
"// 3 component magnitude calculation using the vtkDataArray API.\n"
"// Inefficient, but easy to write:\n"
"void calcMagnitude(vtkDataArray *vectors, vtkDataArray *magnitude)\n"
"{\n"
"  vtkIdType numVectors = vectors->GetNumberOfTuples();\n"
"  for (vtkIdType tupleIdx = 0; tupleIdx < numVectors; ++tupleIdx)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // What data types are magnitude and vectors using?\n"
"    // We don't care! These methods all use double.\n"
"    magnitude->SetComponent(tupleIdx, 0, std::sqrt(\n"
"      vectors->GetComponent(tupleIdx, 0) * vectors->GetComponent(tupleIdx, "
"0) +\n"
"      vectors->GetComponent(tupleIdx, 1) * vectors->GetComponent(tupleIdx, "
"1) +\n"
"      vectors->GetComponent(tupleIdx, 2) * vectors->GetComponent(tupleIdx, "
"2));\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:108
msgid "The Costs of Flexibility"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:110
msgid ""
"However, this flexibility comes at a cost. Passing data through a generic "
"API has a number of issues:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:113
msgid "Accuracy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:115
msgid ""
"Not all ValueTypes are fully expressible as a `double`. The truncation of "
"integers with > 52 bits of precision can be a particularly nasty issue."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:118
msgid "Performance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:120
msgid ""
"__Virtual overhead__: The only way to implement such a system is to route "
"the `vtkDataArray` calls through a run-time resolution of ValueTypes. This "
"is implemented through the virtual override mechanism of C++, which adds a "
"small overhead to each API call."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:125
msgid ""
"__Missed optimization__: The virtual indirection described above also "
"prevents the compiler from being able to make assumptions about the layout "
"of the data in-memory. This information could be used to perform advanced "
"optimizations, such as vectorization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:130
msgid ""
"So what can one do if they want fast, optimized, type-safe access to the "
"data stored in a `vtkDataArray` or `vtkAbstractArray`? What options are "
"available?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:133
msgid "The Old Solution: vtkTemplateMacro"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:135
msgid ""
"The `vtkTemplateMacro`, or its extension `vtkExtendedTemplateMacro` (adds "
"`VTK_STRING`) and `vtkExtraExtendedTemplateMacro` (adds `VTK_STRING`, "
"`VTK_VARIANT`) is described in this section. While it is no longer "
"considered a best practice to use this construct in new code, it is still "
"usable and likely to be encountered when reading the VTK source code. Newer "
"code should use the `vtkArrayDispatch` mechanism, which is detailed later. "
"The discussion of `vtkTemplateMacro` will help illustrate some of the "
"practical issues with array dispatching."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:144
msgid ""
"With a few minor exceptions that we won't consider here, prior to VTK 7.1 it "
"was safe to assume that all numeric `vtkDataArray` objects were also "
"subclasses of `vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate`, which at the time was called "
"`vtkDataArrayTemplate`. This template class provided the implementation of "
"all documented numeric data arrays such as `vtkDoubleArray`, "
"`vtkIdTypeArray`, etc., and stores the tuples in memory as a contiguous "
"array-of-structs (AOS). For example, if we had an array that stored 3-"
"component tuples as floating point numbers, we could define a tuple as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:152
msgid "struct Tuple { float x; float y; float z; };\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:156
msgid ""
"An array-of-structs, or AOS, memory buffer containing this data could be "
"described as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:159
msgid "Tuple ArrayOfStructsBuffer[NumTuples];\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:163
msgid ""
"As a result, `ArrayOfStructsBuffer` will have the following memory layout:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:165
msgid "{ x1, y1, z1, x2, y2, z2, x3, y3, z3, ...}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:169
msgid ""
"That is, the components of each tuple are stored in adjacent memory "
"locations, one tuple after another. While this is not exactly how "
"`vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate` implemented its memory buffers, it accurately "
"describes the resulting memory layout."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:174
msgid ""
"Combine the AOS memory convention and `GetDataType()` with a horrific little "
"method on the data arrays named `GetVoidPointer()`, and a path to efficient, "
"type-safe access was available. `GetVoidPointer()` does what it says on the "
"tin: it returns the memory address for the array data's base location as a "
"`void*`. While this breaks encapsulation and sets off warning bells for the "
"more pedantic among us, the following technique was safe and efficient when "
"used correctly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:182
msgid ""
"// 3-component magnitude calculation using GetVoidPointer.\n"
"// Efficient and fast, but assumes AOS memory layout\n"
"template <typename ValueType>\n"
"void calcMagnitudeWorker(ValueType* vectors, ValueType* magnitude, vtkIdType "
"numVectors)\n"
"{\n"
"  for (vtkIdType tupleIdx = 0; tupleIdx < numVectors; ++tupleIdx)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // We now have access to the raw memory buffers, and assuming\n"
"    // AOS memory layout, we know how to access them.\n"
"    magnitude[tupleIdx] = std::sqrt(\n"
"      vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 0] * vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 0] +\n"
"      vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 1] * vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 1] +\n"
"      vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 2] * vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 2]);\n"
"   }\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"void calcMagnitude(vtkDataArray* vectors, vtkDataArray* magnitude)\n"
"{\n"
"  assert(\"Arrays must have same datatype!\" &&\n"
"         vtkDataTypesCompare(vectors->GetDataType(),\n"
"                             magnitude->GetDataType()));\n"
"  switch (vectors->GetDataType())\n"
"  {\n"
"    vtkTemplateMacro(calcMagnitudeWorker<VTK_TT*>(\n"
"      static_cast<VTK_TT*>(vectors->GetVoidPointer(0)),\n"
"      static_cast<VTK_TT*>(magnitude->GetVoidPointer(0)),\n"
"      vectors->GetNumberOfTuples());\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:214
msgid ""
"The `vtkTemplateMacro`, as you may have guessed, expands into a series of "
"case statements that determine an array's ValueType from the `int "
"GetDataType()` return value. The ValueType is then `typedef`'d to `VTK_TT`, "
"and the macro's argument is called for each numeric type returned from "
"`GetDataType`. In this case, the call to `calcMagnitudeWorker` is made by "
"the macro, with `VTK_TT` `typedef`'d to the array's ValueType."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:221
msgid ""
"This is the typical usage pattern for `vtkTemplateMacro`. The "
"`calcMagnitude` function calls a templated worker implementation that uses "
"efficient, raw memory access to a typesafe memory buffer so that the "
"worker's code can be as efficient as possible. But this assumes AOS memory "
"ordering, and as we'll mention, this assumption may no longer be valid as "
"VTK moves further into the field of in-situ analysis."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:228
msgid ""
"But first, you may have noticed that the above example using "
"`vtkTemplateMacro` has introduced a step backwards in terms of "
"functionality. In the `vtkDataArray` implementation, we didn't care if both "
"arrays were the same ValueType, but now we have to ensure this, since we "
"cast both arrays' `void` pointers to `VTK_TT`*. What if vectors is an array "
"of integers, but we want to calculate floating point magnitudes?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:235
msgid "vtkTemplateMacro with Multiple Arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:237
msgid ""
"The best solution prior to VTK 7.1 was to use two worker functions. The "
"first is templated on vector's ValueType, and the second is templated on "
"both array ValueTypes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:241
msgid ""
"// 3-component magnitude calculation using GetVoidPointer and a\n"
"// double-dispatch to resolve ValueTypes of both arrays.\n"
"// Efficient and fast, but assumes AOS memory layout, lots of boilerplate\n"
"// code, and the sensitivity to template explosion issues increases.\n"
"template <typename VectorType, typename MagnitudeType>\n"
"void calcMagnitudeWorker2(VectorType* vectors, MagnitudeType* magnitude,\n"
"                          vtkIdType numVectors)\n"
"{\n"
"  for (vtkIdType tupleIdx = 0; tupleIdx < numVectors; ++tupleIdx)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // We now have access to the raw memory buffers, and assuming\n"
"    // AOS memory layout, we know how to access them.\n"
"    // We now have access to the raw memory buffers, and assuming\n"
"    // AOS memory layout, we know how to access them.\n"
"    magnitude[tupleIdx] = std::sqrt(\n"
"      vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 0] * vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 0] +\n"
"      vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 1] * vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 1] +\n"
"      vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 2] * vectors[3 * tupleIdx + 2]);\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"// Vector ValueType is known (VectorType), now use vtkTemplateMacro on\n"
"// magnitude:\n"
"template <typename VectorType>\n"
"void calcMagnitudeWorker1(VectorType* vectors, vtkDataArray* magnitude,\n"
"                          vtkIdType numVectors)\n"
"{\n"
"  switch (magnitude->GetDataType())\n"
"  {\n"
"    vtkTemplateMacro(calcMagnitudeWorker2(vectors,\n"
"      static_cast<VTK_TT*>(magnitude->GetVoidPointer(0)), numVectors);\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
"\n"
"void calcMagnitude(vtkDataArray *vectors, vtkDataArray *magnitude)\n"
"{\n"
"  // Dispatch vectors first:\n"
"  switch (vectors->GetDataType())\n"
"  {\n"
"    vtkTemplateMacro(calcMagnitudeWorker1<VTK_TT*>(\n"
"      static_cast<VTK_TT*>(vectors->GetVoidPointer(0)),\n"
"      magnitude, vectors->GetNumberOfTuples());\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:288
msgid ""
"This works well, but it's a bit ugly and has the same issue as before "
"regarding memory layout. Double dispatches using this method will also see "
"more problems regarding binary size. The number of template instantiations "
"that the compiler needs to generate is determined by `I = T^D`, where `I` is "
"the number of template instantiations, `T` is the number of types "
"considered, and `D` is the number of dispatches. As of VTK 7.1, "
"`vtkTemplateMacro` considers 14 data types, so this double-dispatch will "
"produce 14 instantiations of `calcMagnitudeWorker1` and 196 instantiations "
"of `calcMagnitudeWorker2`. If we tried to resolve 3 `vtkDataArray`s into raw "
"C arrays, 2744 instantiations of the final worker function would be "
"generated. As more arrays are considered, the need for some form of "
"restricted dispatch becomes very important to keep this template explosion "
"in check."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:301
msgid "Data Array Changes in newer VTK"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:303
msgid ""
"Starting with VTK 7.1, the Array-Of-Structs (AOS) memory layout is no longer "
"the only `vtkDataArray` implementation provided by the library. The Struct-"
"Of-Arrays (SOA) memory layout is now available through the "
"`vtkSOADataArrayTemplate` class. The SOA layout assumes that the components "
"of an array are stored separately, as in:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:309
msgid ""
"struct StructOfArraysBuffer\n"
"{\n"
"  float *x; // Pointer to array containing x components\n"
"  float *y; // Same for y\n"
"  float *z; // Same for z\n"
"};\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:318
msgid ""
"The new SOA arrays were added to improve interoperability between VTK and "
"simulation packages for live visualization of in-situ results. Many "
"simulations use the SOA layout for their data, and natively supporting these "
"arrays in VTK will allow analysis of live data without the need to "
"explicitly copy it into a VTK data structure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:324
msgid ""
"As a result of this change, a new mechanism is needed to efficiently access "
"array data. `vtkTemplateMacro` and `GetVoidPointer` are no longer an "
"acceptable solution -- implementing `GetVoidPointer` for SOA arrays requires "
"creating a deep copy of the data into a new AOS buffer, a waste of both "
"processor time and memory. Even if someone is willing to pay the cost of "
"this copy, `GetVoidPointer` could only be used to read data from the SOA "
"array, not write to it, so it would be of limited use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:332
msgid ""
"So we need a replacement for `vtkTemplateMacro` that can abstract away "
"things like storage details while providing performance that is on-par with "
"raw memory buffer operations (when possible). And while we're at it, let's "
"look at removing the tedium of multi-array dispatch and reducing the problem "
"of 'template explosion'. The remainder of this page details such a system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:338
msgid "Best Practices for vtkDataArray access"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:340
msgid ""
"We'll describe a new set of tools that make managing template instantiations "
"for efficient array access both easy and extensible. As an overview, the "
"following new features will be discussed:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:344
msgid ""
"`vtkGenericDataArray`: The new templated base interface for all numeric "
"`vtkDataArray` subclasses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:346
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch`: Collection of code generation tools that allow concise "
"and precise specification of restrictable dispatch for up to 3 "
"`vtkAbstractArray`s simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:349
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDownCast`: Access to specialized downcast implementations from code "
"templates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:351
msgid ""
"`vtk::DataArrayValueRange<TupleSize = vtk::detail::DynamicTupleSize, "
"ForceValueTypeForVtkDataArray = double>()`: Range-based for loop support for "
"`vtkAbstractArray` subclasses that abstracts away storage details and allows "
"efficient access of values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:354
msgid ""
"`vtk::DataArrayTupleRange<TupleSize = vtk::detail::DynamicTupleSize>()`: "
"Range-based for loop support for `vtkAbstractArray` subclasses that "
"abstracts away storage details and allows efficient access of values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:357
msgid ""
"`vtkDataArrayAccessor`: A helper class that provides a single API for "
"accessing/inserting values/tuples in any `vtkDataArray` subclass. This class "
"was the predecessor of `vtk::DataArray(Value/Tuple)Range`. It should only be "
"used when inserting is required, and not for value/tuple access, because "
"it's not as optimized."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:361
msgid ""
"These will be discussed more fully, but as a preview, here's our familiar "
"`calcMagnitude` example implemented using these new tools:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:364
msgid ""
"// Modern implementation of calcMagnitude using new concepts in VTK:\n"
"// A worker functor. The calculation is implemented in the function "
"template\n"
"// for operator().\n"
"struct CalcMagnitudeWorker\n"
"{\n"
"  // The worker accepts VTK array objects now, not raw memory buffers.\n"
"  template <typename VectorArray, typename MagnitudeArray>\n"
"  void operator()(VectorArray* vectorsArray, MagnitudeArray* "
"magnitudeArray)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // These allow this single worker function to be used with both\n"
"    // the vtkDataArray 'double' API and the more efficient\n"
"    // vtkGenericDataArray APIs, depending on the template parameters:\n"
"    auto vectors = vtk::DataArrayTupleRange<3>(vectorsArray);\n"
"    auto magnitude = vtk::DataArrayValueRange<1>(magnitudeArray);\n"
"\n"
"    vtkIdType numVectors = vectorsArray->GetNumberOfTuples();\n"
"    for (vtkIdType tupleIdx = 0; tupleIdx < numVectors; ++tupleIdx)\n"
"    {\n"
"      // These operataors[] compile to inlined optimizable raw memory "
"accesses\n"
"      // for vtkGenericDataArray subclasses.\n"
"      magnitude[tupleIdx] = std::sqrt(\n"
"        vectors[tupleIdx][0] * vectors[tupleIdx][0] +\n"
"        vectors[tupleIdx][1] * vectors[tupleIdx][1] +\n"
"        vectors[tupleIdx][2] * vectors[tupleIdx][2]);\n"
"    }\n"
"  }\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
"void calcMagnitude(vtkDataArray *vectors, vtkDataArray *magnitude)\n"
"{\n"
"  // Create our worker functor:\n"
"  CalcMagnitudeWorker worker;\n"
"\n"
"  // Define our dispatcher. We'll let vectors have any ValueType, but only\n"
"  // consider float/double arrays for magnitudes. These combinations will\n"
"  // use a 'fast-path' implementation generated by the dispatcher:\n"
"  using Dispatcher = vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByValueType\n"
"    <\n"
"      vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes, // ValueTypes allowed by first array\n"
"      vtkArrayDispatch::Reals     // ValueTypes allowed by second array\n"
"    >;\n"
"\n"
"  // Execute the dispatcher:\n"
"  if (!Dispatcher::Execute(vectors, magnitude, worker))\n"
"  {\n"
"    // If Execute() fails, it means the dispatch failed due to an\n"
"    // unsupported array type. In this case, it's likely that the magnitude\n"
"    // array is using an integral type. This is an uncommon case, so we "
"won't\n"
"    // generate a fast path for these, but instead call an instantiation of\n"
"    // CalcMagnitudeWorker::operator()<vtkDataArray, vtkDataArray>.\n"
"    // Through the use of vtk::DataArrayTupleRange, this falls back to using "
"the\n"
"    // vtkDataArray double API:\n"
"    worker(vectors, magnitude);\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:422
msgid "vtkGenericDataArray"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:424
msgid ""
"The `vtkGenericDataArray` class template drives the new `vtkDataArray` class "
"hierarchy. The ValueType is introduced here, both as a template parameter "
"and a class-scope `typedef`. This allows a typed API to be written that "
"doesn't require conversion to/from a common type (as `vtkDataArray` does "
"with double). It does not implement any storage details, however. Instead, "
"it uses the CRTP idiom to forward key method calls to a derived class "
"without using a virtual function call. By eliminating this indirection, "
"`vtkGenericDataArray` defines an interface that can be used to implement "
"highly efficient code, because the compiler is able to see past the method "
"calls and optimize the underlying memory accesses instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:435
msgid ""
"There are two main subclasses of `vtkGenericDataArray`: "
"`vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate` and `vtkSOADataArrayTemplate`. These implement "
"array-of-structs and struct-of-arrays storage, respectively. Recently, "
"`vtkImplicitArray` was added, which is also a subclass of "
"`vtkGenericDataArray`, and is used to implement read-only arrays using a "
"given backend. We won't go into detail how this is done, but one could look "
"into `vtkConstantArray` and `vtkAffineArray` which are examples of "
"`vtkImplicitArray` subclasses."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:442
msgid "vtkTypeList"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:444
msgid ""
"Type lists are a metaprogramming construct used to generate a list of C++ "
"types. They are used in VTK to implement restricted array dispatching. As we "
"will see, `vtkArrayDispatch` offers ways to reduce the number of generated "
"template instantiations by enforcing constraints on the arrays used to "
"dispatch. For instance, if one wanted to only generate templated worker "
"implementations for `vtkFloatArray` and `vtkIntArray`, a typelist is used to "
"specify this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:451
msgid ""
"// Create a typelist of 2 types, vtkFloatArray and vtkIntArray:\n"
"using MyArrays = vtkTypeList::Create<vtkFloatArray, vtkIntArray>;\n"
"\n"
"Worker someWorker = ...;\n"
"vtkDataArray *someArray = ...;\n"
"\n"
"// Use vtkArrayDispatch to generate code paths for these arrays:\n"
"vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByArray<MyArrays>(someArray, someWorker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:462
msgid ""
"There's not much to know about type lists as a user, other than how to "
"create them. As seen above, there is a set of macros named `vtkTypeList::"
"Create<...>`, where X is the number of types in the created list, and the "
"arguments are the types to place in the list. In the example above, the new "
"type list is typically bound to a friendlier name using a local `typedef`, "
"which is a common practice."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:469
msgid ""
"The `vtkTypeList.h` header defines some additional type list operations that "
"may be useful, such as deleting and appending types, looking up indices, "
"etc. `vtkArrayDispatch::FilterArraysByValueType` may come in handy, too. But "
"for working with array dispatches, most users will only need to create new "
"ones, or use one of the following predefined `vtkTypeLists`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:475
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Reals`: All floating point ValueTypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:476
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Integrals`: All integral ValueTypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:477
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes`: Union of Reals and Integrals."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:478
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::AOSArrays`: Default list of AOS ArrayTypes to use in "
"dispatches, which is filled if `CMake` option `VTK_DISPATCH_AOS_ARRAYS` is "
"on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:480
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::SOAArrays`: Default list of SOA ArrayTypes to use in "
"dispatches, which is filled if `CMake` option `VTK_DISPATCH_SOA_ARRAYS` is "
"on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:482
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays`: Default list of read/write ArrayTypes to use in "
"dispatches, which is a union of `AOSArrays` and `SOAArrays`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:484
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::AffineArrays`: Default list of affine ArrayTypes to use "
"in dispatches, which is filled if `CMake` option "
"`VTK_DISPATCH_AFFINE_ARRAYS` is on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:486
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::ConstantArrays`: Default list of constant ArrayTypes to "
"use in dispatches, which is filled if `CMake` option "
"`VTK_DISPATCH_CONSTANT_ARRAYS` is on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:488
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::StridedArrays`: Default list of strided ArrayTypes to use "
"in dispatches, which is filled if `CMake` option "
"`VTK_DISPATCH_STRIDED_ARRAYS` is on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:490
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::StructuredPointArrays`: Default list of structured point "
"ArrayTypes to use in dispatches, which is filled if `CMake` option "
"`VTK_DISPATCH_STRUCTURED_POINT_ARRAYS` is on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:492
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::ReadOnlyArrays`: Default list of read-only ArrayTypes to "
"use in dispatches, which is union of `AffineArrays`, `ConstantArrays`, "
"`StridedArrays`, and `StructuredPointArrays`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:494
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::AllArrays`: Union of `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` and "
"`vtkArrayDispatch::ReadOnlyArrays`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:496
msgid ""
"There are also some additional predefined `vtkTypeLists` in "
"`vtkArrayDispatchDataSetArrayList.h`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:498
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::AOSPointArrays`: Float and double AOS arrays that are "
"commonly used for point coordinates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:499
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::PointArrays`: Float and double AOS and SOA arrays that "
"are commonly used for point coordinates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:500
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::AllPointArrays`: Float and double AOS, SOA, "
"StructuredPoint arrays that are commonly used for point coordinates."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:502
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::ConnectivityArrays`: `vtkTypeInt32` and `vtkTypeInt64` "
"AOS arrays that are commonly used for cell connectivity."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:504
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::OffsetsArrays`: `vtkTypeInt32` and `vtkTypeInt64` AOS and "
"Affine arrays that are commonly used for cell offsets."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:506
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::CellTypesArrays`: unsigned char AOS and Constant arrays "
"that are commonly used for cell types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:508
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` is a special typelist of ArrayTypes set "
"application-wide when VTK is built. This `vtkTypeList` of `vtkDataArray` "
"subclasses is used for unrestricted dispatches, and is the list that gets "
"filtered when restricting a dispatch to specific ValueTypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:512
msgid ""
"Refining `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` or `vtkArrayDispatch::AllArrays` can be "
"done using the aforementioned `CMake` options `VTK_DISPATCH_*_ARRAYS`, and "
"allows the user building VTK to have some control over the dispatch process. "
"If SOA arrays (or others) are never going to be used, they can be removed "
"from dispatch calls, reducing compile times and binary size. On the other "
"hand, a user applying in-situ techniques may want them available, because "
"they'll be used to import views of intermediate results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:519
msgid "vtkArrayDownCast"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:521
msgid ""
"In VTK, all subclasses of `vtkObject` (including the data arrays) support a "
"downcast method called `SafeDownCast`. It is used similarly to the C++ "
"`dynamic_cast` -- given an object, try to cast it to a more derived type or "
"return `nullptr` if the object is not the requested type. Say we have a "
"`vtkDataArray` and want to test if it is actually a `vtkFloatArray`. We can "
"do this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:528
msgid ""
"void DoSomeAction(vtkDataArray *dataArray)\n"
"{\n"
"  vtkFloatArray *floatArray = vtkFloatArray::SafeDownCast(dataArray);\n"
"  if (floatArray)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // ... (do work with float array)\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:539
msgid ""
"This works, but it can pose a serious problem if `DoSomeAction` is called "
"repeatedly. `SafeDownCast` works by performing a series of virtual calls and "
"string comparisons to determine if an object falls into a particular class "
"hierarchy. These string comparisons add up and can actually dominate "
"computational resources if an algorithm implementation calls `SafeDownCast` "
"in a tight loop."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:546
msgid ""
"In such situations, it's ideal to restructure the algorithm so that the "
"downcast only happens once and the same result is used repeatedly, but "
"sometimes this is not possible. To lessen the cost of downcasting arrays, a "
"`FastDownCast` method exists for all concrete subclasses of "
"`vtkAbstractArray`. This replaces the string comparisons with a single "
"virtual call and a few integer comparisons and is far cheaper than the more "
"general SafeDownCast. However, not all array implementations support the "
"`FastDownCast` method, such as a vtkImplicitArray with a backend that is not "
"publicly defined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:555
msgid "This creates a headache for templated code. Take the following example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:557
msgid ""
"template <typename ArrayType>\n"
"void DoSomeAction(vtkAbstractArray *array)\n"
"{\n"
"  ArrayType *myArray = ArrayType::SafeDownCast(array);\n"
"  if (myArray)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // ... (do work with myArray)\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:569
msgid ""
"We cannot use `FastDownCast` here since not all possible ArrayTypes support "
"it. But we really want that performance increase for the ones that do -- "
"`SafeDownCast`s are really slow! `vtkArrayDownCast` fixes this issue:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:573
msgid ""
"template <typename ArrayType>\n"
"void DoSomeAction(vtkAbstractArray *array)\n"
"{\n"
"  ArrayType *myArray = vtkArrayDownCast<ArrayType>(array);\n"
"  if (myArray)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // ... (do work with myArray)\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:585
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDownCast` automatically selects `FastDownCast` when it is defined "
"for the ArrayType, and otherwise falls back to `SafeDownCast`. This is the "
"preferred array downcast method for performance, uniformity, and reliability."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:589
msgid "vtk::DataArrayValueRange and vtk::DataArrayTupleRange"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:591
msgid ""
"Array dispatching relies on having templated worker code carry out some "
"operation. For instance, take this `vtkArrayDispatch` code that locates the "
"maximum value in an array:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:595
msgid ""
"// Stores the tuple/component coordinates of the maximum value:\n"
"struct FindMax\n"
"{\n"
"  vtkIdType Tuple; // Result\n"
"  int Component; // Result\n"
"\n"
"  FindMax() : Tuple(-1), Component(-1) {}\n"
"\n"
"  template <typename ArrayT>\n"
"  void operator()(ArrayT* array)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // The type to use for temporaries, and a temporary to store\n"
"    // the current maximum value:\n"
"    typedef typename ArrayT::ValueType ValueType;\n"
"    ValueType max = std::numeric_limits<ValueType>::min();\n"
"\n"
"    // Iterate through all tuples and components, noting the location\n"
"    // of the largest element found.\n"
"    vtkIdType numTuples = array->GetNumberOfTuples();\n"
"    int numComps = array->GetNumberOfComponents();\n"
"    for (vtkIdType tupleIdx = 0; tupleIdx < numTuples; ++tupleIdx)\n"
"    {\n"
"      for (int compIdx = 0; compIdx < numComps; ++compIdx)\n"
"      {\n"
"        if (max < array->GetTypedComponent(tupleIdx, compIdx))\n"
"        {\n"
"          max = array->GetTypedComponent(tupleIdx, compIdx);\n"
"          this->Tuple = tupleIdx;\n"
"          this->Component = compIdx;\n"
"        }\n"
"      }\n"
"    }\n"
"  }\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
"void someFunction(vtkDataArray *array)\n"
"{\n"
"  FindMax maxWorker;\n"
"  vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch::Execute(array, maxWorker);\n"
"  // Do work using maxWorker.Tuple and maxWorker.Component...\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:639
msgid ""
"There's a problem, though. Recall that only the arrays in `vtkArrayDispatch::"
"Arrays` are tested for dispatching. What happens if the array passed into "
"someFunction wasn't on that list?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:643
msgid ""
"The dispatch will fail, and `maxWorker.Tuple` and `maxWorker.Component` will "
"be left to their initial values of -1. That's no good. What if "
"`someFunction` is a critical path where we want to use a fast dispatched "
"worker if possible, but still have valid results to use if dispatching "
"fails? Well, we can fall back on the `vtkDataArray` API and do things the "
"slow way in that case. When a dispatcher is given an unsupported array, "
"Execute() returns false, so let's just add a backup implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:651
msgid ""
"// Stores the tuple/component coordinates of the maximum value:\n"
"struct FindMax\n"
"{ /* As before... */ };\n"
"\n"
"void someFunction(vtkDataArray *array)\n"
"{\n"
"  FindMax maxWorker;\n"
"  if (!vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch::Execute(array, maxWorker))\n"
"  {\n"
"    // Reimplement FindMax::operator(), but use the vtkDataArray API's\n"
"    // \"virtual double GetComponent()\" instead of the more efficient\n"
"    // \"ValueType GetTypedComponent()\" from vtkGenericDataArray.\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:668
msgid ""
"Ok, that works. But ugh...why write the same algorithm twice? That's extra "
"debugging, extra testing, extra maintenance burden, and just plain not fun."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:671
msgid ""
"So here is where `vtk::DataArrayValueRange` and `vtk::DataArrayTupleRange` "
"come in."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:673
msgid ""
"`vtk::DataArrayValueRange` provides a range-based for loop interface to "
"access the elements of a `vtkAbstractArray` subclass as if it's a simple "
"flat array, like `std::vector<ValueType>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:675
msgid ""
"`vtk::DataArrayTupleRange` provides a similar interface, but presents the "
"data as a set of tuples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:678
msgid ""
"Both of these utilities work with both `vtkAbstractArray` and `vtkDataArray` "
"concrete subclasses and `vtkDataArray` too, using the most efficient access "
"method available for the given array type. abstract away the storage details "
"of the underlying array, allowing efficient access to the data regardless of "
"whether the array is AOS, SOA, or some other storage scheme."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:683
msgid ""
"The also provide C++11 range-based for loop support, making iterating "
"through the data easy and less error-prone, along with functions like "
"`size()` to get the number of values/tuples in the array. If the tuple size "
"is known at compile time, it can be provided as a template parameter to "
"`vtk::DataArrayTupleRange`, allowing for further optimizations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:688
msgid ""
"`vtk::DataArrayValueRange` also has a second template parameter, "
"`ForceValueTypeForVtkDataArray`, which allows the user to specify the type "
"to use when the underlying array is a `vtkDataArray`. This is useful when "
"the user wants to avoid the default double type for `vtkDataArray`s. A "
"usefully utility is `vtk::GetAPIType<ArrayType>`, which returns the "
"corresponding ValueType for concrete subclasses and double for "
"`vtkDataArray`. Both these utilities provide similar funct"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:695
msgid ""
"Using `vtk::DataArray(Tuple/Value)Range`, we can write a single worker "
"template that works for both `vtkDataArray` and `vtkGenericDataArray`, "
"without a loss of performance in the latter case. That worker looks like "
"this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:699
msgid ""
"// Better, uses vtk::DataArrayTupleRange:\n"
"struct FindMax\n"
"{\n"
"  vtkIdType Tuple; // Result\n"
"  int Component; // Result\n"
"\n"
"  FindMax() : Tuple(-1), Component(-1) {}\n"
"\n"
"  template <typename ArrayT>\n"
"  void operator()(ArrayT* array)\n"
"  {\n"
"    // Create the range:\n"
"    auto range = vtk::DataArrayTupleRange(array);\n"
"\n"
"    // Prepare the temporary.\n"
"    using ValueType = vtk::GetAPIType<ArrayT>;\n"
"    ValueType max = std::numeric_limits<ValueType>::min();\n"
"\n"
"    vtkIdType numTuples = array->GetNumberOfTuples();\n"
"    int numComps = array->GetNumberOfComponents();\n"
"    for (auto tuple : range)\n"
"    {\n"
"      for (auto comp : tuple)\n"
"      {\n"
"        if (max < comp)\n"
"        {\n"
"          max = comp;\n"
"          this->Tuple = tupleIdx;\n"
"          this->Component = compIdx;\n"
"        }\n"
"      }\n"
"    }\n"
"  }\n"
"};\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:736
msgid ""
"Now when we call `operator()` with say, `ArrayT=vtkFloatArray`, we'll get an "
"optimized, efficient code path. But we can also call this same "
"implementation with `ArrayT=vtkDataArray` and still get a correct result "
"(assuming that the `vtkDataArray`'s double API represents the data well "
"enough)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:741
msgid ""
"Using the `vtkDataArray` fallback path is straightforward. At the call site:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:743
msgid ""
"void someFunction(vtkDataArray *array)\n"
"{\n"
"  FindMax maxWorker;\n"
"  if (!vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch::Execute(array, maxWorker))\n"
"  {\n"
"    maxWorker(array); // Dispatch failed, call vtkDataArray fallback\n"
"  }\n"
"  // Do work using maxWorker.Tuple and maxWorker.Component -- now we know\n"
"  // for sure that they're initialized!\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:756
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:758
msgid ""
"The dispatchers implemented in the vtkArrayDispatch namespace provide array "
"dispatching with customizable restrictions on code generation and a simple "
"syntax that hides the messy details of type resolution and multi-array "
"dispatch. There are several \"flavors\" of dispatch available that operate "
"on up to three arrays simultaneously."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:764
msgid "Components Of A Dispatch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:766
msgid ""
"Using the `vtkArrayDispatch` system requires three elements: the array(s), "
"the worker, and the dispatcher."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:769
msgid "The Arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:771
msgid ""
"All dispatched arrays must be concrete subclasses of `vtkAbstractArray`. It "
"is important to identify as many restrictions as possible. Must every "
"ArrayType be considered during dispatch, or is the array's ValueType (or "
"even the ArrayType itself) restricted? If dispatching multiple arrays at "
"once, are they expected to have the same ValueType? These scenarios are "
"common, and these conditions can be used to reduce the number of "
"instantiations of the worker template."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:778
msgid "The Worker"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:780
msgid ""
"The worker is some generic callable. In C++98, a templated functor is a good "
"choice. In C++14, a generic lambda is a usable option as well. For our "
"purposes, we'll only consider the functor approach,, but since VTK 9.5 "
"requires C++17, generic lambdas should work just fine as workers, too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:785
msgid ""
"At a minimum, the worker functor should define `operator()` to make it "
"callable. This should be a function template with a template parameter for "
"each array it should handle. For a three array dispatch, it should look "
"something like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:790
msgid ""
"struct ThreeArrayWorker\n"
"{\n"
"  template <typename Array1T, typename Array2T, typename Array3T>\n"
"  void operator()(Array1T* array1, Array2T* array2, Array3T* array3)\n"
"  {\n"
"    /* Do stuff... */\n"
"  }\n"
"};\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:801
msgid ""
"At runtime, the dispatcher will call `ThreeWayWorker::operator()` with a set "
"of `Array1T`, `Array2T`, and `Array3T` that satisfy any dispatch "
"restrictions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:804
msgid ""
"Workers can be stateful, too, as seen in the `FindMax` worker earlier where "
"the worker simply identified the component and tuple id of the largest value "
"in the array. The functor stored them for the caller to use in further "
"analysis:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:808
msgid ""
"// Example of a stateful dispatch functor:\n"
"struct FindMax\n"
"{\n"
"  // Functor state, holds results that are accessible to the caller:\n"
"  vtkIdType Tuple;\n"
"  int Component;\n"
"\n"
"  // Set initial values:\n"
"  FindMax() : Tuple(-1), Component(-1) {}\n"
"\n"
"  // Template method to set Tuple and Component ivars:\n"
"  template <typename ArrayT>\n"
"  void operator()(ArrayT *array)\n"
"  {\n"
"    /* Do stuff... */\n"
"  }\n"
"};\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:828
msgid "The Dispatcher"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:830
msgid ""
"The dispatcher is the workhorse of the system. It is responsible for "
"applying restrictions, resolving array types, and generating the requested "
"template instantiations. It has responsibilities both at run-time and "
"compile-time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:834
msgid ""
"During compilation, the dispatcher will identify the valid combinations of "
"arrays that can be used according to the restrictions. This is done by "
"starting with a typelist of arrays, either supplied as a template parameter "
"or by defaulting to `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays`, and/or filtering them by "
"ValueType if needed. For multi-array dispatches, additional restrictions may "
"apply, such as forcing the second and third arrays to have the same "
"ValueType as the first. It must then generate the required code for the "
"dispatch -- that is, the templated worker implementation must be "
"instantiated for each valid combination of arrays. These implementation are "
"stored in an array and can be accessed at runtime using `GetDataType` and "
"`GetArrayType` with `O(1)` complexity, if their array type is listed in the "
"`vtkArrayTypes` enum."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:846
msgid ""
"At runtime, the dispatcher can either get the correct implementation with "
"`O(1)` complexity (most common), or if the provided are not regular VTK "
"arrays, it tests each of the dispatched arrays to see if they match one of "
"the generated code paths. Runtime type resolution is carried out using "
"`vtkArrayDownCast` to get the best performance available for the arrays of "
"interest. If it finds a match, it calls the worker's `operator()` method "
"with the properly typed arrays. If no match is found, it returns `false` "
"without executing the worker."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:854
msgid "Restrictions: Why They Matter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:856
msgid ""
"We've made several mentions of using restrictions to reduce the number of "
"template instantiations during a dispatch operation. You may be wondering if "
"it really matters so much. Let's consider some numbers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:860
msgid ""
"VTK is configured to use 13 ValueTypes for numeric data. These are the "
"standard numeric types `float`, `int`, `unsigned char`, etc. By default, VTK "
"will define `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` to use all 13 types with "
"`vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate` for the standard set of dispatchable arrays. If "
"enabled during compilation, the SOA data arrays are added to this list for a "
"total of 26 arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:866
msgid ""
"Using these 26 arrays in a single, unrestricted dispatch will result in 26 "
"instantiations of the worker template. A double dispatch will generate 676 "
"workers. A triple dispatch with no restrictions creates a whopping 17,576 "
"functions to handle the possible combinations of arrays. That's a _lot_ of "
"instructions to pack into the final binary object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:872
msgid ""
"Applying some simple restrictions can reduce this immensely. Say we know "
"that the arrays will only contain `float`s or `double`s. This would reduce "
"the single dispatch to 4 instantiations, the double dispatch to 16, and the "
"triple to 64. We've just reduced the generated code size significantly. "
"Dispatch restriction is a powerful tool for reducing the compiled size of a "
"binary object."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:878
msgid ""
"Another common restriction is that all arrays in a multi-array dispatch have "
"the same ValueType, even if that ValueType is not known at compile time. By "
"specifying this restriction, a double dispatch on all 26 AOS/SOA arrays will "
"only produce 52 worker instantiations, down from 676. The triple dispatch "
"drops to 104 instantiations from 17,576."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:884
msgid ""
"Always apply restrictions when they are known, especially for multi-array "
"dispatches. The savings are worth it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:887
msgid "Types of Dispatchers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:889
msgid ""
"Now that we've discussed the components of a dispatch operation, what the "
"dispatchers do, and the importance of restricting dispatches, let's take a "
"look at the types of dispatchers available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:895
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:897
msgid ""
"This family of dispatchers take no parameters and perform an unrestricted "
"dispatch over all arrays in `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:900
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:929
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:982
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1027
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1073
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1104
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1153
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1200
msgid "__Variations__:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:902
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch`: Single dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:903
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2`: Double dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:904
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3`: Triple dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:906
msgid "__Arrays considered__: All arrays in `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:908
msgid "__Restrictions__: None."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:910
msgid ""
"__Usecase__: Used when no useful information exists that can be used to "
"apply restrictions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:913
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:941
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:997
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1042
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1089
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1119
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1168
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1216
msgid "__Example Usage__:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:915
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch::Execute(array, worker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:921
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByArray"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:923
msgid ""
"This family of dispatchers takes a `vtkTypeList` of explicit array types to "
"use during dispatching. They should only be used when an array's exact type "
"is restricted. If dispatching multiple arrays and only one has such type "
"restrictions, use `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` (or a filtered version) for the "
"unrestricted arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:931
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByArray`: Single dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:932
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByArray`: Double dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:933
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3ByArray`: Triple dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:935
msgid ""
"__Arrays considered__: All arrays explicitly listed in the parameter lists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:937
msgid ""
"__Restrictions__: Array must be explicitly listed in the dispatcher's type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:939
msgid "__Use case__: Used when one or more arrays have known implementations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:943
msgid ""
"An example here would be a filter that processes an input array of some "
"integral type and produces either a `vtkDoubleArray` or a `vtkFloatArray`, "
"depending on some condition. Since the input array's implementation is "
"unknown (it comes from outside the filter), we'll rely on a ValueType-"
"filtered version of `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` for its type. However, we "
"know the output array is either `vtkDoubleArray` or `vtkFloatArray`, so "
"we'll want to be sure to apply that restriction:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:951
msgid ""
"// input has an unknown implementation, but an integral ValueType.\n"
"vtkDataArray *input = ...;\n"
"\n"
"// Output is always either vtkFloatArray or vtkDoubleArray:\n"
"vtkDataArray *output = someCondition ? vtkFloatArray::New()\n"
"                                     : vtkDoubleArray::New();\n"
"\n"
"// Define the valid ArrayTypes for input by filtering\n"
"// vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays to remove non-integral types:\n"
"using InputTypes = vtkArrayDispatch::FilterArraysByValueType<\n"
"  vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays, vtkArrayDispatch::Integrals>::Result;\n"
"\n"
"// For output, create a new vtkTypeList with the only two possibilities:\n"
"using OutputTypes = vtkTypeList::Create<vtkFloatArray, vtkDoubleArray>;\n"
"\n"
"// Typedef the dispatch to a more manageable name:\n"
"using Dispatcher = vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByArray<InputTypes, "
"OutputTypes>;\n"
"\n"
"// Execute the dispatch:\n"
"Dispatcher::Execute(input, output, someWorker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:976
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByValueType"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:978
msgid ""
"This family of dispatchers takes a vtkTypeList of ValueTypes for each array "
"and restricts dispatch to only arrays in vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays that have "
"one of the specified value types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:984
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByValueType`: Single dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:985
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByValueType`: Double dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:986
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3ByValueType`: Triple dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:988
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1158
msgid ""
"__Arrays considered__: All arrays in `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` that meet "
"the ValueType requirements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:991
msgid ""
"__Restrictions__: Arrays that do not satisfy the ValueType requirements are "
"eliminated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:994
msgid ""
"__Use case__: Used when one or more of the dispatched arrays has an unknown "
"implementation, but a known (or restricted) ValueType."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:999
msgid ""
"Here we'll consider a filter that processes three arrays. The first is a "
"complete unknown. The second is known to hold `unsigned char`, but we don't "
"know the implementation. The third holds either `double`s or `float`s, but "
"its implementation is also unknown."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1004
msgid ""
"// Complete unknown:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array1 = ...;\n"
"// Some array holding unsigned chars:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array2 = ...;\n"
"// Some array holding either floats or doubles:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array3 = ...;\n"
"\n"
"// Typedef the dispatch to a more manageable name:\n"
"using Dispatcher = vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3ByValueType<\n"
"  vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes, vtkTypeList::Create<unsigned char>, "
"vtkArrayDispatch::Reals>;\n"
"\n"
"// Execute the dispatch:\n"
"Dispatcher::Execute(array1, array2, array3, someWorker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1022
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByArrayAndValueType"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1024
msgid ""
"This family of dispatchers takes a `vtkTypeList` of explicit array types to "
"use during dispatching, and a `vtkTypeList` of ValueTypes to consider during "
"dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1029
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByArrayAndValueType`: Single dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1030
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByArrayAndValueType`: Double dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1031
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3ByArrayAndValueType`: Triple dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1033
msgid ""
"__Arrays considered__: All arrays explicitly listed in the parameter lists "
"that also have ValueTypes in the ValueType typelists."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1036
msgid ""
"__Restrictions__: Array must be explicitly listed in the dispatcher's type, "
"and its ValueType must be in the ValueType typelist."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1039
msgid ""
"__Use case__: Used when one or more arrays have known implementations, but "
"those implementations have unknown ValueTypes, and the ValueTypes are "
"restricted in some way."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1044
msgid ""
"The example shown for `vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByArray` can also be "
"implemented using this family of dispatchers as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1047
msgid ""
"// input has an unknown implementation, but an integral ValueType.\n"
"vtkDataArray *input = ...;\n"
"\n"
"// Output is always either vtkFloatArray or vtkDoubleArray:\n"
"vtkDataArray *output = someCondition ? vtkFloatArray::New()\n"
"                                     : vtkDoubleArray::New();\n"
"\n"
"// Define the valid ArrayTypes for input by filtering\n"
"// vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays to remove non-integral types:\n"
"using Dispatcher = vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByArrayAndValueType<\n"
"  vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays, vtkArrayDispatch::AOSArrays,\n"
"  vtkArrayDispatch::Integrals, vtkArrayDispatch::Reals>;\n"
"\n"
"// Execute the dispatch:\n"
"Dispatcher::Execute(input, output, someWorker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1067
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch*SameValueType"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1069
msgid ""
"This family of dispatchers requires that all dispatched arrays share a "
"ValueType, considering all arrays from `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` across "
"`vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes` with no additional ValueType restriction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1075
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2SameValueType`: Double dispatch using "
"`vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1077
msgid ""
"`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3SameValueType`: Triple dispatch using "
"`vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1080
msgid ""
"__Arrays considered__: All arrays in `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` across all "
"ValueTypes in `vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1083
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1112
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1161
#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1208
msgid ""
"__Restrictions__: Combinations of arrays with differing ValueTypes are "
"eliminated."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1086
msgid ""
"__Use case__: When all arrays are known to share the same ValueType but no "
"further restriction on which ValueType is known, regardless of "
"implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1091
msgid ""
"vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2SameValueType::Execute(a1, a2, worker);\n"
"vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3SameValueType::Execute(a1, a2, a3, worker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1098
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::DispatchByArray*WithSameValueType"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1100
msgid ""
"This family of dispatchers takes a `vtkTypeList` of ArrayTypes for each "
"array and restricts dispatch to only consider arrays from those typelists, "
"with the added requirement that all dispatched arrays share a ValueType."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1106
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByArrayWithSameValueType`: Double dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1107
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3ByArrayWithSameValueType`: Triple dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1109
msgid ""
"__Arrays considered__: All arrays in the explicit typelists that meet the "
"ValueType requirements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1115
msgid ""
"__Use case__: When one or more arrays are known to belong to a restricted "
"set of ArrayTypes, and all arrays are known to share the same ValueType, "
"regardless of implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1121
msgid ""
"Let's consider a double array dispatch, with `array1` known to be one of "
"four common array types (SOA `float`, `double`, `int`, and `vtkIdType` "
"arrays), and the other is an AOS and we know that it holds the same "
"ValueType as `array1`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1125
msgid ""
"// SOA float, double, int, or vtkIdType array:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array1 = ...;\n"
"// AOS implementation, but the ValueType matches array1:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array2 = ...;\n"
"\n"
"// array1's possible types:\n"
"using Array1Types =\n"
"  vtkTypeList::Create<vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<float>, "
"vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<double>,\n"
"  vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<int>, vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<vtkIdType>>;\n"
"\n"
"// Typedef the dispatch to a more manageable name:\n"
"using Dispatcher =\n"
"  vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByArrayWithSameValueType<Array1Types, "
"vtkArrayDispatch::AOSArrays>;\n"
"\n"
"// Execute the dispatch:\n"
"Dispatcher::Execute(array1, array2, someWorker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1146
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch*BySameValueType"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1148
msgid ""
"This family of dispatchers takes a single `vtkTypeList` of ValueType and "
"restricts dispatch to only consider arrays from `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` "
"with those ValueTypes, with the added requirement that all dispatched arrays "
"share a ValueType."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1155
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2BySameValueType`: Double dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1156
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3BySameValueType`: Triple dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1164
msgid ""
"__Use case__: When one or more arrays are known to belong to a restricted "
"set of ValueTypes, and all arrays are known to share the same ValueType, "
"regardless of implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1170
msgid ""
"Let's consider a double array dispatch, with `array1` known to be one of "
"four common ValueTypes (`float`, `double`, `int`, and `vtkIdType` arrays), "
"and `array2` known to have the same ValueType as `array1`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1174
msgid ""
"// Some float, double, int, or vtkIdType array:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array1 = ...;\n"
"// Unknown, but the ValueType matches array1:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array2 = ...;\n"
"\n"
"// The allowed ValueTypes:\n"
"using ValidValueTypes = vtkTypeList::Create<float, double, int, vtkIdType>;\n"
"\n"
"// Typedef the dispatch to a more manageable name:\n"
"using Dispatcher = vtkArrayDispatch::"
"Dispatch2BySameValueType<ValidValueTypes>;\n"
"\n"
"// Execute the dispatch:\n"
"Dispatcher::Execute(array1, array2, someWorker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1192
msgid "vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch*ByArrayAndSameValueType"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1194
msgid ""
"This family of dispatchers takes both a `vtkTypeList` of array types "
"(`ArrayList`) and a `vtkTypeList` of ValueTypes (`ValueTypeList`), "
"restricting dispatch to only consider array types found in `ArrayList` that "
"have a ValueType contained in `ValueTypeList`, with the added requirement "
"that all dispatched arrays share a ValueType."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1202
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByArrayAndSameValueType`: Double dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1203
msgid "`vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch3ByArrayAndSameValueType`: Triple dispatch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1205
msgid ""
"__Arrays considered__: All arrays found in `ArrayList` whose ValueType is "
"contained in `ValueTypeList`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1211
msgid ""
"__Use case__: When all arrays are known to belong to a specific set of array "
"implementations and ValueTypes, and all arrays are known to share the same "
"ValueType. Use `vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes` for `ValueTypeList` to consider "
"all ValueTypes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1218
msgid ""
"Let's consider a double array dispatch, with `array1` and `array2` known to "
"be AOS arrays with a ValueType of `float`, `double`, `int`, or `vtkIdType`, "
"and `array2` known to have the same ValueType as `array1`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1222
msgid ""
"// Some AOS float, double, int, or vtkIdType array:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array1 = ...;\n"
"// Unknown, but the ValueType matches array1:\n"
"vtkDataArray *array2 = ...;\n"
"\n"
"// The allowed ValueTypes:\n"
"using ValidValueTypes = vtkTypeList::Create<float, double, int, vtkIdType>;\n"
"\n"
"// Typedef the dispatch to a more manageable name:\n"
"using Dispatcher = vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByArrayAndSameValueType\n"
"    vtkArrayDispatch::AOSArrays, ValidValueTypes>;\n"
"\n"
"// Execute the dispatch:\n"
"Dispatcher::Execute(array1, array2, someWorker);\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1241
msgid "Advanced Usage"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1243
msgid "Accessing Memory Buffers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1245
msgid ""
"Despite the thin `vtkGenericDataArray` API's nice feature that compilers can "
"optimize memory accesses, sometimes there are still legitimate reasons to "
"access the underlying memory buffer. This can still be done safely by "
"providing overloads to your worker's `operator()` method. For instance, "
"`vtkDataArray::DeepCopy` uses a generic implementation when mixed array "
"implementations are used, but has optimized overloads for copying between "
"arrays with the same ValueType and implementation. The worker for this "
"dispatch is shown below as an example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1254
msgid ""
"// Copy tuples from src to dest:\n"
"struct DeepCopyWorker\n"
"{\n"
"  // AoS --> AoS same-type specialization:\n"
"  template <typename ValueType>\n"
"  void operator()(vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate<ValueType>* src,\n"
"                  vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate<ValueType>* dst)\n"
"  {\n"
"    std::copy_n(src->GetPointer(0), src->GetNumberOfValues(), dst-"
">GetPointer(0));\n"
"  }\n"
"\n"
"  // SoA --> SoA same-type specialization:\n"
"  template <typename ValueType>\n"
"  void operator()(vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<ValueType>* src,\n"
"                  vtkSOADataArrayTemplate<ValueType>* dst)\n"
"  {\n"
"    for (int comp; comp < src->GetNumberOfComponents(); ++comp)\n"
"    {\n"
"      std::copy_n(src->GetComponentArrayPointer(comp), src-"
">GetNumberOfTuples(),\n"
"        dst->GetComponentArrayPointer(comp));\n"
"    }\n"
"  }\n"
"\n"
"  // Generic implementation:\n"
"  template <typename Array1T, typename Array2T>\n"
"  void operator()(Array1T* srcArray, Array2T* dstArray)\n"
"  {\n"
"    auto src = vtk::DataArrayTupleRange(srcArray);\n"
"    auto dst = vtk::DataArrayTupleRange(dstArray);\n"
"\n"
"    using DestType = vtk::GetAPIType<Array2T>;\n"
"\n"
"    vtkIdType tuples = src->GetNumberOfTuples();\n"
"    int comps = src->GetNumberOfComponents();\n"
"    for (vtkIdType t = 0; t < tuples; ++t)\n"
"    {\n"
"      for (int c = 0; c < comps; ++c)\n"
"      {\n"
"        dst[t][c] = static_cast<DestType>(src[t][c]);\n"
"      }\n"
"    }\n"
"  }\n"
"};\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1300
msgid "Putting It All Together"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1302
msgid ""
"Now that we've explored the new tools introduced with VTK that allow "
"efficient, implementation agnostic array access, let's take another look at "
"the `calcMagnitude` example from before and identify the key features of the "
"implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1306
msgid ""
"// Modern implementation of calcMagnitude using new concepts in VTK:\n"
"struct CalcMagnitudeWorker\n"
"{\n"
"  void operator()(VectorArray* vectorsArray, MagnitudeArray* "
"magnitudeArray)\n"
"  {\n"
"    auto vectors = vtk::DataArrayTupleRange<3>(vectorsArray);\n"
"    auto magnitude = vtk::DataArrayValueRange<1>(magnitudeArray);\n"
"\n"
"    vtkIdType numVectors = vectorsArray->GetNumberOfTuples();\n"
"    for (vtkIdType tupleIdx = 0; tupleIdx < numVectors; ++tupleIdx)\n"
"    {\n"
"      // These operataors[] compile to inlined optimizable raw memory "
"accesses\n"
"      // for vtkGenericDataArray subclasses.\n"
"      magnitude[tupleIdx] = std::sqrt(\n"
"        vectors[tupleIdx][0] * vectors[tupleIdx][0] +\n"
"        vectors[tupleIdx][1] * vectors[tupleIdx][1] +\n"
"        vectors[tupleIdx][2] * vectors[tupleIdx][2]);\n"
"    }\n"
"  }\n"
"};\n"
"\n"
"void calcMagnitude(vtkDataArray *vectors, vtkDataArray *magnitude)\n"
"{\n"
"  CalcMagnitudeWorker worker;\n"
"  using Dispatcher = vtkArrayDispatch::Dispatch2ByValueType<\n"
"    vtkArrayDispatch::AllTypes, vtkArrayDispatch::Reals>;\n"
"\n"
"  if (!Dispatcher::Execute(vectors, magnitude, worker))\n"
"  {\n"
"    worker(vectors, magnitude); // vtkDataArray fallback\n"
"  }\n"
"}\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1341
msgid "This implementation:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1343
msgid ""
"Uses dispatch restrictions to reduce the number of instantiated templated "
"worker functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1345
msgid "Assuming 26 types are in `vtkArrayDispatch::Arrays` (13 AOS + 13 SOA)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1346
msgid "The first array is unrestricted. All 26 array types are considered."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1347
msgid ""
"The second array is restricted to `float` or `double` ValueTypes, which "
"translates to 4 array types (one each, SOA and AOS)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1349
msgid ""
"26 * 4 = 104 possible combinations exist. We've eliminated 26 * 22 = 572 "
"combinations that an unrestricted double-dispatch would have generated (it "
"would create 676 instantiations)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1352
msgid ""
"The calculation is still carried out at `double` precision when the "
"ValueType restrictions are not met."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1354
msgid ""
"Just because we don't want those other 572 cases to have special code "
"generated doesn't necessarily mean that we wouldn't want them to run."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1356
msgid ""
"Thanks to `vtk::DataArray(Value/Tuple)Range`, we have a fallback "
"implementation that reuses our templated worker code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1358
msgid ""
"In this case, the dispatch is really just a fast-path implementation for "
"floating point output types."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1360
msgid ""
"The performance should be identical to iterating through raw memory buffers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1361
msgid ""
"The `vtkGenericDataArray` API is transparent to the compiler. The "
"specialized instantiations of `operator()` can be heavily optimized since "
"the memory access patterns are known and well-defined."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1365
msgid ""
"Guidelines to remove/reduce vtkAbstractArray::GetVoidPointer() usages from "
"your codebase"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1367
msgid ""
"As we have already mentioned, `vtkAbstractArray::GetVoidPointer()` is a "
"function that returns a raw pointer to the underlying data of a VTK array. "
"This function was added in VTK's early days when it only supported "
"`vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate` arrays. Since then, VTK has added support for "
"multiple other array types, either explicit (e.g., "
"`vtkSOADataArrayTemplate`, etc.) or implicit (e.g., `vtkAffineArray`, "
"`vtkConstantArray`, etc.). These array types don't store their data in a "
"contiguous block of memory, so using `GetVoidPointer()` leads to duplication "
"of data in an internal `vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate` array, which leads to "
"memory usage increase and unnecessary copying overhead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1376
msgid ""
"The following guidelines can be used to remove the usage of "
"`GetVoidPointer()`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1378
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate/vtkBitArray/vtkmDataArray`, use "
"`GetPointer()` instead of `GetVoidPointer()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1379
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkSOADataArrayTemplate`, and only a single component is "
"needed, use `GetComponentArrayPointer()` instead of `GetVoidPointer()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1381
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkDataArray` and all tuples need to be filled, use `Fill` "
"instead of `memset()` with `GetVoidPointer()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1383
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkAbstractArray` and all tuples need to be copied, use "
"`DeepCopy()/ShallowCopy()` instead of `memcpy()` with `GetVoidPointer()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1385
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkAbstractArray` and some tuples need to be copied, use "
"`InsertTuples*()` methods instead of `GetVoidPointer()` and `memcpy()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1387
msgid ""
"If two `vtkAbstractArray`s need to be compared, use `vtkTestUtilities::"
"CompareAbstractArray()` instead of `GetVoidPointer()` and `std::equal()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1389
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkAbstractArray` and values are needed as `vtkVariant`, use "
"`GetVariantValue()` instead of `vtkExtraExtendedTemplateMacro` with "
"`GetVoidPointer()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1391
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkAbstractArray` and access to the tuples/values is needed, "
"use `vtkArrayDispatch` and `vtk::DataArray(Value/Tuple)Range()`, instead of "
"`vtkTemplateMacro` (or other variations) with `GetVoidPointer()`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1393
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkDataArray`, the data type is known, and raw pointer to data "
"is absolutely needed, use `auto aos = array->ToAOSDataArray()`, and then use "
"`vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate<Type>::FastDownCast(aos)->GetPointer()`, instead of "
"`GetVoidPointer()`, being aware that this may lead to data duplication if "
"the array is not `vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1398
msgid ""
"The following guidelines can be used to ensure that using `GetVoidPointer()` "
"is _safe_:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1400
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkDataArray`, but using `HasStandardMemoryLayout`, it has been "
"verified that it actually is `vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate`, then "
"`GetVoidPointer()` is _safe_ to use. This usually happens when the array was "
"created using `vtkAbstractArray::CreateArray()` or `vtkDataArray::"
"CreateDataArray()` by passing a standard VTK data type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1403
msgid ""
"If array is `vtkDataArray`, the data type is NOT known, but raw pointer to "
"data is absolutely needed, use `auto aos = array->ToAOSDataArray()`, and "
"then use `aos->GetVoidPointer()`, which is _safe_, being aware that this may "
"lead to data duplication if the array is not `vtkAOSDataArrayTemplate`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../design_documents/ArrayDispatch.md:1407
msgid ""
"Finally, `vtkAbstractArray::GetVoidPointer()` and `vtkDataArray::"
"GetVoidPointer()` have been marked as an _unsafe_ function using `clang-"
"tidy`, and its usage will be warned as such, unless explicitly marked as "
"_safe_ using the `(bugprone-unsafe-functions)` lint, upon guaranteeing that "
"it is indeed safe to use, if and only if, it satisfies one of the two "
"conditions mentioned above."
msgstr ""
